or=#A62A2A>(10/22/02 4:55:38 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=785.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Table Top Gamers</span><hr size=1> &lt;gasp&gt;  You mentioned Torg!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   One of my favorite systems because of the flexible mechanics; the card playing and possibility using that allow the player to &quot;cheat&quot; bad rolls to make a neater thing happen.  That's one thing that frustrates me about most roleplaying games, that I'd prefer the game to play out like an interesting novel, with dramatic combat scenes, which was something nice about the Freeform Roleplaying I used to do.<br>
<br>
My ideal game (the game that I wish someone would invite me to participate in, hehe) would be long term, fantasy-based rather than modern or futuristic, and would contain epic, world-changing storylines.  Characters would start fairly weak and/or young and would work their way up in power.<br>
<br>
One major rule would be that characters would not start inter-party fighting, unless it was part of a major dramatic event, just because I've seen way too much inter-party conflict that either caused problems between the players OOC, or was just petty and stupid (like when the party spends 40 minutes thinking up a plan to deceive a camp of enemies, and one character blithely throws it all away in such a deliberate and idiotic way just because he doesn't like one of the other party members, apparently roleplaying the alignment of &quot;chaotic stupid&quot; - which of course prompts some of the other party members to turn on him in the middle of the camp, etc etc, just ruining the realistic RP mood).<br>
<br>
To foster working together, the characters would probably have to be kind of created in such a way that they would have a reason to work together, like encouraging the players to create characters following the same deity, or of the same race, maybe some of the same family, and certainly of the same or similar alignment.  Definitely each having some compelling reason to go on the campaign.<br>
<br>
I would rather have my gamemaster give me some definite guidelines on character creation rather than having him say, &quot;So you are in this tavern in X town, I don't know why, but you just are...  And something happens and it's just obvious to you for some reason that you should investigate.&quot;  It's not going to ruin the game for me if the GM tells me to make a character that's a police detective or whatever it is.  It'll just make it more interesting to me to be able to roleplay something that makes sense for the setting.<br>
<br>
I can also enjoy a real hack and slash dungeon crawler, and if that's what I know we're going for I'm going to break out the uber stats.  I just don't like creating a character with personality and having that personality ignored.<br>
Like the time I created a rogue that was weak in combat but quite strong in charisma, allure and guile, and whenever I tried to talk to/persuade any NPCs about anything they ignored me.  Either give the players some guidelines and some idea of how the game is going to be played, or tailor the game to the characters a little more.<br>
<br>
I have a few character archetypes that I usually play.  Usually I play charismatic characters that like to talk their way out of things, only attacking if there's no other choice (except in the aforementioned hack &amp; slash games, when I'll usually play a surly, strong person).  Many of them have low wisdom and are the extremely confident, fearless type that would take almost any dare.<br>
My characters are invariably good in alignment, unless the particular game is specifically an &quot;evil party&quot; game or Vampire game or something.<br>
I had a great time once playing a snooty, yet good-hearted noble Elven minstrel in one of the more roleplayish AD&amp;D games I was in, who'd run away from home to seek fame and adventure, and ended up half falling for the somewhat uncouth Wood Elven ranger.<br>
<br>
I usually like to play a spellcaster or healer type, though tougher fighters can be fun as well.  I've had characters of all types over the years.<br>
<br>
Well, that's probably more like 82 cents than 2 cents, but I'm suffering from insomnia and rambling. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/usmallcutepuppy.showPublicProfile?language=EN>smallcutepuppy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 562<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/22/02 7:17:04 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=785.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Table Top Gamers</span><hr size=1> Number One thing I look for is a mature roleplaying group.<br>
<br>
Once you have that it doesn't matter what system you use. Personally I tend to just use the books for inspiration, have people roll up a character so I have a reference point, then I make them hand me all their character sheets and I do all the rolling myself out of their sight. Most of the time I don't even use the game's dice rules, unless for some reason I find them particularly appropriate; I just mentally assign an impromptu difficulty, roll 2d10 and improvise what happens based on that.<br>
<br>
