<br>
You baiscally declared yourself a fighter or magic type.  You could learn any skill you wanted, but to cross types costed you extra points.  Made sense to me.<br>
<br>
I prefered the simplicity because I did not get tied up in keeping up with a bunch of stats and could focus on the action and roleplay.  Nothing got to me more than trying to run a game in another system and having that &quot;problem&quot; player that could quote rules by page number and argue what they &quot;ment.&quot;<br>
<br>
When DMing, I always held individual sessions with players to start the backstory and to flesh out the characters.  Was alot better than &quot;You meet in a bar, summoned by a strange note; not knowing each other at all.&quot;  Shoot, it used to take me as long as 4 months before I'd bring the group back together for party adventurers.<br>
<br>
I miss those days... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=thewthunderstrike>ThewThunderstrike</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 12<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/23/02 11:39:11 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=785.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  My best RP experience was in Valparaiso.</span><hr size=1> <br>
Valpo High School gaming club in 1990-1991.<br>
<br>
Most of the people there were also in National Honors Society or the Quiz Bowl Club.  A few of us were on the cross country team together too.<br>
<br>
The Best GM's were the Juniors and Seniors.  I was just a freshman.  We played almost every night after school in the cafeteria.  Then we started playing at eachothers houses.<br>
<br>
It was a magical experience.  Truely magnificent.  I have role played since, but nothing compares to that year, to the stories we wove, and the adventures we had.<br>
<br>
<br>
Mostly we played AD&amp;D, but also Shadowrun, Paladin, and a WWII game (can't remember the name).<br>
<br>
My dad got a new job out of state at the end of that year, and  I moved with my parents to Ohio, where my new school didn't even have a games club.  <br>
<br>
Though I started a new games club, the school made us call it a Chess and Games club, because roleplaying was kind of taboo.<br>
<br>
It was never the same.  I participated very few tabletop rpgs during the rest of highschool, but they sucked and I got wrapped up in other extra curriculars.  I got to put &quot;president and founder of the chess club&quot; on my college application, next to a bunch of other crap.  Though after my sophomore year I left it to persue other activities.<br>
<br>
Nonetheless, I continue to read the books I started reading in 1990, starting with RA Salvatores novels.  I have moved on from RA Salvatore (though am still within the genre)except for his Daemon Wars Series for which I await the next release.<br>
<br>
<br>
sigh...<br>
<br>
I can remember parts of it like it was just yesterday.  GOD IT WAS FUN.<br>
<br>
<br>
/salute<br>
<br>
p.s.<br>
I never got over Valparaiso. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=cylria>Cylria</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 87<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/24/02 11:38:25 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=785.topic&index=13>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: My favorite</span><hr size=1> I agree that a good group can make any RPG system work. It seems that I always have at least one power gamer to deal with so I tend to favor flexible, but well balanced systems that are easy to police. The best ruleset for that is the HERO system. The D20 system (3rd ed D&amp;D) is my current second favorite.<br>
